evon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Nythway, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1355–1420":"1355–1420","1351–1432":"1351–1432","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1372–1450":"1372–1450","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1361–1440":"1361–1440","1384–1473":"1384–1473","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1330":"1330","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1423":"1423","1355":"1355","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","about 1356":"circa 1356","Abt 1380":"circa 1380","about 1384":"circa 1384","Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England":"Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Nythway, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1355–1420":"1355–1420","1351–1432":"1351–1432","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1372–1450":"1372–1450","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1361–1440":"1361–1440","1384–1473":"1384–1473","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1330":"1330","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1423":"1423","1355":"1355","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","about 1356":"about 1356","Abt 1380":"about 1380","about 1384":"about 1384","Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England":"Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Nythway, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cole","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Colton","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire): habitational name from any of various places called Colton in England. Examples in Norfolk, Staffordshire, and North Yorkshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (or the cognate Old Norse <i>Koli</i>; see   Cole   2) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The place so named in Somerset has as its first element the Old English personal name <i>Cūla</i> (of uncertain origin). The one in Cumbria has a river name apparently derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘hazel’. This English name is also common in Ireland; it was the name of a bishop of Derry in 1397. There seems also to have been confusion with   Culliton  .","Scottish and Irish (Monaghan): shortened and altered form of Gaelic <b>Mac Haldan</b>, ‘son of <i>Haldan</i>’, see   Haldane  ."]},{"name":"Colclough","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Cheshire): habitational name from Cowclough in the parish of Whitworth, Lancashire, earlier recorded as <i>Colleclogh</i>, probably named with the Old English byname <i>Cola</i> (see   Cole   2) + Old English <i>clōh</i> ‘ravine’."]},{"name":"Calcote","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in Bedfordshire, Berkshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Northamptonshire, Warwickshire, and elsewhere) named Caldecote or Caldecott, from Old English <i>cald</i> ‘cold’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, dwelling’. It has been suggested that in Old English this expression denoted an unattended shelter for wayfarers, although in fact some places with this name were of considerable status by 1086, when they appear in Domesday Book. In some instances this and some of the other shortened forms may have arisen from Calcot in Berkshire, Collacott(s) in Devon, or Calcutt in Wiltshire, in all of which the first element apparently comes from the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (see   Cole   2) or the word <i>col</i> ‘(char)coal’, in which case the meaning would be something like ‘coalshed’."]},{"name":"Collignon","meanings":["French and Walloon: from a shortened pet form (see   Cole   and   Colle  ) of the French personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  )."]},{"name":"Colling","meanings":["English (northern England and Devon): from the Old Norse personal name <i>Kollungr</i>, a derivative of <i>Koli</i>, or from Old English <i>Colling</i>, a derivative of <i>Cola</i> (see   Cole  ). Alternatively, from a pet form of the personal name <i>Col(l)</i>, a pet form of   Nicholas   (see also   Colin  ).","German: variant of   Kolling   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Collard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Donat, Normand, Octave, Adelard, Aldor, Andre, Armand, Emile, Germaine, Marcel.","English (southern), French, and Walloon: from a diminutive of the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nic(h)olas</i> (see   Cole  ), formed with the Old French suffix <i>-ard</i>."]},{"name":"Coale","meanings":["English: post-medieval form of   Cole  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Coles","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cole  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Nichol","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Nic(h)ol(e)</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Nic(h)olas</i> (see   Nicholas  ). Compare   Nickel   and   Nicol  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Greek   Nikolas  , its variant   Nicolas  , or of any of various derivatives of the personal name <i>Nikola(o)s</i> ‘Nicholas’, including <b>Nikolis</b> (see   Nicoli  ). Compare   Nicholas   and   Nicol  ."]},{"name":"Coalson","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Cole  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When William Cole Esq. was born in 1355, in Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England, his father, Sir John Cole, was 25 and his mother, Anne de Bodrugan - Heiress of Nythway, was 18. He married Margarete Beaupell in 1382, in Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1420, in his hometown, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1355–1420":"1355–1420","1351–1432":"1351–1432","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1372–1450":"1372–1450","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1361–1440":"1361–1440","1384–1473":"1384–1473","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1330":"1330","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1423":"1423","1355":"1355","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","about 1356":"umbes 1356","Abt 1380":"umbes 1380","about 1384":"umbes 1384","Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England":"Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Nythway, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1355–1420":"1355–1420","1351–1432":"1351–1432","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1372–1450":"1372–1450","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1361–1440":"1361–1440","1384–1473":"1384–1473","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1330":"1330","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1423":"1423","1355":"1355","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","about 1356":"noin 1356","Abt 1380":"noin 1380","about 1384":"noin 1384","Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England":"Brixham, Torbay, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Nythway, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1355–1420":"1355–1420","1351–1432":"1351–1432","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1372–1450":"1372–1450","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1361–1440":"1361–1440","1384–1473":"1384–1473","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1330":"1330","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1423":"1423","1355":"1355","1432":"1432",